segments.text: centralized planning functions for the state and to assist communities were dismantled by the succeeding governor.
Who was?
Who was?
Who was the next governor?
Dolph, the evaporative.
Dolph Briscoe.
Right, Dolph Briscoe, who spent very little time being governor and apparently was anti-planning.
He certainly put together an anti-planning staff.
They
They also had some very undemocratic procedures that they followed.
I'm afraid it was very much of the era of the old-time Texans, wherein you did what you wanted with your stuff.
They had a very difficult time understanding that the federal government had guidelines for the use of money that people received from the federal government.
At any rate, I'm going to get through the rest of my personal history kind of quickly so we can talk about whatever else we need to talk about planning.
After I left Newhouse and Taylor, I went to work with Carter Otscott, and the planning that I did there was split into two sorts of things.
I did do a couple of comprehensive plans that they sort of had left over from the days when they thought that there was a value in the 701 program and still had a commitment to finish up.
They were at that point doing an enormous amount of
campus planning for major universities, which are sort of a microcosm.
They're an interesting blend between a company town and a dictatorship.
Campuses are a dictatorship?
Certainly are.
And who's the dictator varies a great deal from campus to campus.
At any rate, the campus plans were very interesting.
They involved the communities into them, some more than others.
We wanted to do the total thing together wherever it was possible to do that.
And then a lot of planning oriented to large-scale architectural projects.
some of which were the equivalent of cities in themselves.
In some cases, I spent three or four days being the consultant to something that was going to have a major impact on some city, a giant new hospital complex, for instance.
But at any rate, I spent five or six years working there and then joined Bernstaff.
I guess the other thing, the one thing that Vernon would like to mention was that he was president of the Gulf of Southwest chapter of AIP, which has now been merged into APA.
He was president when I arrived in Texas in 1969, as I recall.
He probably was.
Yes.
He had been the Houston section director.
I've been the Houston section director.
I've been president of the Texas chapter of AIP.
I was also an officer in CPAP.
which is confined to people who are employed by cities in Texas.
There have been a bunch of things that we have worked on with other people to accomplish within those organizations.
One thing that I think that was reasonably remarkable that I was involved in along

with one of the planners from the Dallas-Fort Worth area was the writing of the enabling legislation for regional planning commissions, which we did as a part of our CPAT activities and passed on to the Texas Municipal League, who found the support for it and got it passed.
They, however, removed all of the, the Texas Municipal League removed from our recommendations before they passed on all of the ability for taxation.

that it wouldn't fly that way oh date that's interesting well I suspect that it was probably in the vicinity of 1964 but I don't remember exactly when I think the regional planning legislation was probably passed by the 65 legislature 63 or 65 in the early 60s
I don't know what else.
I think that covers the essential points of history so that you would understand how my comments are during the period of time that I worked at CRS.

Virtually all the things I did were in other parts of the United States so that I had a five-year gap in my association with Houston things and a good comparison towards what was being done in other parts of the country.
And I observed, in general, that when you compare things to a city like Philadelphia, which at that point was touted to be the great mecca of planning, I discovered that, in my opinion, it was not.
There were a lot of people involved in functions that had planning somewhere in their title.
But what they were mainly doing was jealously guarding their own little bailiwick, and there was very little cooperation going on.
It took an enormous amount of time and effort, most of which was unproductive, to accomplish anything in Philadelphia.
Was that during the Ed Bacon regime?
Yes, it was during Ed Bacon's regime.
I think that the majority of the planning things that were so highly...
touted in Philadelphia were, in fact, largely physical design elements and didn't have a lot to do with some of the hardcore basics of real planning.
There is now a backlash in the planning department because of that.
And the pendulum has swung to the other extreme, unfortunately.
Really?
That is too bad.
I have documentation on this because of the book I'm working on.
And I'd hope to use Philadelphia as an example of continuation of the comprehensive planning process, but I'm afraid I cannot.
That's such a bad.
One of the things that I was involved in in Philadelphia had to do with Eastwick, which must be one of the world's greatest planning disasters.
And as a part, just because I was curious about it, I delved into some of the background information
scrunched up some of the old reports, and I understood why it turned out to be such a disaster.
Did you meet Bill Grigsby?
No.
Who had done the market feasibility study for Eastwick?
No.
He was now the head of the planning department at the University of Pennsylvania.
Uh-huh.
I may have met him since, but I didn't meet him yet.
OK, what else do you want to talk about?
The single biggest event that went on during the time that I was president of the Texas chapter of AIB.
And you were elected in what year?
I have to count backwards.
We're now in 81.
Probably 1977, so the merger was accomplished in 78.
And before that I was the Texas chapter secretary, and before that I had been the Houston
section director.
So I've really been on the executive committee for a very long time.
The single biggest thing that happened while I was president was the merger between AIP and ASCO.
And the consideration of that merger and the various implications used up a lot of time at the chapter level as well as the national level.
It was very difficult to keep ongoing programs and things that we had decided that we wanted to accomplish as a group
going on while there was a consideration of changing the entire nature of the organization.
I personally was opposed to the merger.
And I have discovered that a large number of people who are very active within APA now, even at the national level, were also opposed to it.
Everybody has sort of shrugged their shoulders and said, OK, we decided to do it.
And now we're going to do our best to make it work.
And I think most people are doing their best to make it work.
However, I will observe that the net effect of what we did has little effect at the chapter level other than to increase the volume of membership.
It has not increased the number of active members.
It has not changed the active people.
The new active people are still
coming from the same place as they were.
There are young people entering the profession or people who have moved here from other parts of the state.
They are not civilians involved in planning.
And this, I have found, is generally true throughout my district because I've talked to the presidents of the various chapters in my district, so I don't think we're atypical.
Texas did have a smaller percentage gain in membership than almost anyone else.
as the result of the merger.
And I think that pointed to something that we were maybe not aware of, that a very high percentage of the people who were active in planning in Texas were AIP members of one category or another.
We had an unusually high.
I think that part of that comes from our sheer distances apart and our knowledge that we share the same laws and the same problems.

Most of our cities are developing in the freeway era, and we do have the same problems, and we had a great need to communicate with each other about our problems and offer our good solutions to each other.
In other parts of the country, people tended to be much more insular in their outlook,

that people are flabbergasted that we could have a chapter that, you know, is a thousand miles across and however many miles in the other direction it is, 800 or so, and that we could actually work together, but we do.
At any rate, at the national level, there continues to be a concern about involving the citizens who are interested in planning.
And there continue to be
New suggestions, and mainly they're fairly feeble.
While people, the result of all the screaming in the 60s about people being interested in planning and how they should be interested in planning did generate interest.
People do attend public hearings, although I would suggest that mostly it's the negative interests that attend public hearings.

People, citizens, still are not sufficiently interested in planning to commit large blocks of time or money to learning more about it, even if they have positions of some considerable responsibility on local commissions.
And I think that regardless of what we do at the national level, we've got to be realistic and understand that we are primarily going to be an organization of professional planners.
you asked about the net result on the dues.
For the person who was a full AIP member, there's been very little effect on the dues.
You're paying about the same thing as you would have been paying had AIP continued to exist.
Now I'd have to go back and look at the rate of inflation and look at the old, I don't even remember what associate AIP people were paying.
But I think the dues are generally about the same.
as they might have been.
Let me ask you a final question.
From your perception and knowledge of Houston, what do you think
should happen in the near future in terms of planning in the greater Houston area?
What kinds of things should occur, structural or otherwise?
Well, I think the most important thing that we've got to recognize and come to grips with ways to implement is that it is no longer possible for us to be a single center town.
even though our, quote, downtown area is very active and healthy and continuing to grow, that we have passed into a category of cities more like Chicago and that we do have to have sub-centers.
And we need to do some positive things to allow and promote these sub-centers to happen effectively with the kind of transportation networks, etc.,

In all of the planning that's going on now, we're only talking about serving sub-centers that already exist and that have come into being without the benefit of any formal assistance from a planning standpoint from the governments.
The medical center might be the single exception to that.
But we really need to be looking at sub-centers that are further out.
Perhaps Katy, perhaps the Woodlands is one.
But, you know, we are merely continuing on our way with our normal grid thoroughfare system.
Works fine if you have a residential neighborhood thing and it's attendant commercial stuff.
Doesn't work too well, as we could prove with Galleria, when you get a real center working, your transportation network just collapses.
I think there are a number of, I think I know there are a number of people
in influential positions who are aware of that.

Vernon, who also neglected to mention this, was part of a group of about 30 influential citizens, including the presidents of all the major oil companies, the mayor, the police chief, et cetera, who spent a weekend retreat down at the Tenneco-owned resort community down south and west of town.
And they did discuss the need for sub-centers.
No one can come to grips with the problem, however, of whose property it's going to be on.
And I think that's the crux of the problem.
There have been comments about the role that the planning department is taking at this time.
Do you think that should change?
Certainly.
The planning department is sort of following along
licking at the heels of what's happening.
And they ought to be out there helping the people in the forefront to do the right thing, to make the change, to realize that Houston is transitioning from one kind of a city into another.
And they really are not.
We need some active leadership within the department.
I think that they usually have the bright young minds who could think a lot of the things if they had the sort of philosophical, attitudinal things, directions and assistance.
And I think it isn't just the planning director that they need real help from the mayor and the city council.
I would hope that.
even though I was afraid that the system of changing, the change system of electing city council members would turn out to be to the city's detriment.
So far, it seems that rather than being more of a pork barrel, that is much less of a pork barrel, and that the number of these councilmen who've been elected from districts

have much more compunction to speak out about the needs of the city as a whole and don't have the long-term vested interests by certain money groups and sort of warp the older councilman's thinking around.
I mean we did after this new council did after all these years finally adopt the billboard ordinance that we fought for gee I think I first joined billboards limited 12 years ago
And we made drafts of ordinances.
When the first year I worked for CRS, I drafted a billboard ordinance as a part of one of our civic endeavor things through Billboards Inc. And it's finally been passed.
The chap who eased past John Shanahan in the final runoff.
Yes.
Who I understand is rather good.
Yes, he has turned out to be rather good.
He may not have some of the same credentials as John, but he certainly has some of the same interests.
And he's been very clever about getting some things passed.
I think we've all been very surprised.
At any rate, hopefully this new group of councilmen could assist.
But somewhere, somebody's got to step up with the leadership.
And to me, at this point, it looks as if it may have to come from the private sector.
We may be talking about having to get together a group of prominent citizens.
Well, I think the West Houston Association is a good example
of what's happened as a result of the dearth of planning.
The West Houston Association was formed by a small group of progressive developers whose interests were mainly on the West Side, and they saw that there was nothing going on out there.
A lot of it was from their own self-interest, but they saw that things were not going on out there that needed to go on.
And they made their own association and hired a planner to be director of it, and they are
filling some of the basic informational and accomplishment things that the Houston City Finance Department ought to be doing.
That should be tax supported.
Well, I think this particular group of developers really don't care whether it's tax supported or not.
They just want it done.
And they're probably willing to support it.
But it's a public responsibility, though.
It is a public responsibility.
We're fortunate that there are a bunch of guys who think that they have a public responsibility and are willing
to be involved in it.
But they're getting roads built.
They're pushing to get the parks approved.

It's reminiscent of the early days of planning in Boston, and San Francisco, and so forth, and New York, where the private interests, philanthropic interests, funded regional plans and regional planning programs, such as TELUS in San Francisco, the Regional Plan Association in New York,
and Philane and Boston and so forth.
It's a pity that one has to make comments and see these sorts of things happening in 1981.
Yeah, it is.
Mary Lou, I know you've got a bunch of work hanging fire.
Let's try one more time, Margaret.
Thank you very much.
Good afternoon.
We are at the residence of Ralph and Mrs. Ellefrit,
and we are talking about the role of Mr. Elefret in the initial days of planning in Houston and on up through his retirement from the planning department and subsequent professional activities.
Ralph, would you like to begin?
One of my
first activities when the planning department was formed in March of 1940 was to obtain some background on what had happened in planning in the past.
The city government had just moved from the old city hall, which was also the city market, into the new building, which is now the main city hall with the council chambers.
The only materials that I found were down in the vault of the old

City Hall scattered on the floor some role plans miscellaneous traffic counts that listed the number of automobiles and the number of horse drawn vehicles at certain points in the city and quite a miscellaneous group of information

gradually by talking to others and scouting around I did gain a little background and apparently the first planning of course was the original site of the city itself which extended north from Texas Avenue to the bio and six blocks on either side of the
of Main Street to the east and west, which was laid out as the original town site in 1836 by the Allen brothers.
And this was truly perhaps the most remarkable important planning that has been done in Houston because it gave the downtown area a base of regular streets

all 80 feet wide except Maine which is 90 and it provided a block for the county courthouse and a block for public buildings where the old city hall was located and has this pattern which was expanded

south and also to the east and west for a reasonable distance now includes all of the of the real central business district and it has served extremely well in with the smaller blocks and the wide streets to
to handle the growing density of the city.
And this was a real auspicious beginning.
But of course, beyond this general pattern, the city grew rather wildly.
Most cities are planted on north-south and east-west orientations.
And the original Allen Brothers subdivision seems to be at an angle from that.
Is there some reason for that?
The tradition is that the angle to get the breeze, I really think that is somebody's imagination.
I think that really the alignment of the bow had something to do with it.
And perhaps even the shape of the piece of the original track.
But beyond the old general pattern of the downtown area, since the land ownerships were by meets and bounds and not according to townships and ranges in any regular pattern,
there were many developments at various angles where the streets made bad connections and so forth.
Now the next jump in planning came during the latter part of what was the City Beautiful era before the
before World War I.
In around 1910 to 1913 it appeared that many cities were driven by an impetus of civic design and civic development.
It was the end of the city beautiful era which was just
apparently hitting in Texas both Dallas and Houston became interested in planning.
In 1912 the city government of Houston employed Arthur Comey who was then a young professor from Harvard
to come to Houston and prepare a plan and study.
And he did this and the report was published in 1913.
It was a remarkable study in many respects even though following this report we find practically no evidence of planning or interest in planning until 1922
His proposals for large parks included a site almost identical to Memorial Park in the exact location of what became Herman Park.
And he had several alternate locations for a civic center, one of which is where the present civic center is located.

And even though the many years elapsed and the plan was in a sense forgotten, I'm sure that he implanted ideas and thoughts in people's minds that carried over into the many improvements and important developments
that were later realized.
One of the interesting things about the Comey Report was the accuracy of his population projections from a city of 80,000 to a city of over 500,000.
He took these cities, older and larger cities of the United States,
that had access to deep water and put their population on a graph at the point that Houston was at that time, about 80,000.
Then he projected up a mean line through the growth of those cities which had already occurred
to propose a future growth of Houston.
His 1950 population came out very close to the population that was found in the 1950 census.
I had the pleasure of meeting Arthur Comey
at a planning conference in Detroit in the early 50s.
He was then an elderly man, was no longer teaching, but fortunately he said that he had a number of copies of the report, none of which were available in Houston at the time.
And so he sent us
some copies of the report and these are now available in the planning department.
